  <div class="article-content">
    <section id="the-accidental-cardiac-drug" class="reveal">
      <p>Nobody designed it to protect the heart. That is the first thing to understand about Shingrix, the recombinant zoster vaccine that has been on the market since 2017, recommended by the CDC for adults over 50, and administered to tens of millions of people for the sole purpose of preventing a painful skin rash caused by the reactivation of the varicella-zoster virus — the same virus that causes chickenpox in children.</p>

      <p>The second thing to understand is that it might be one of the most effective cardiovascular interventions we have.</p>

      <p>That is not a sentence anyone expected to write about a shingles shot. But in the span of twelve months, three major studies — from the United States, South Korea, and a global meta-analysis — have converged on the same finding: people who get the shingles vaccine experience dramatically fewer heart attacks, strokes, and cardiovascular deaths. The effect sizes are not subtle. They rival quitting smoking.</p>

      <p>The latest data, presented at the American College of Cardiology's annual meeting in New Orleans on March 30, showed a 46% reduction in major adverse cardiac events among vaccinated adults with existing heart disease. All-cause mortality dropped by 66%. These are the kinds of numbers that, if they came from a new pharmaceutical, would be front-page news for a month.</p>

      <p>They came from a vaccine most people associate with avoiding an itchy rash.</p>
    </section>

    <div class="info-card my-12 reveal">
      <h4 class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold mb-3 text-primary-700 dark:text-primary-400">ACC.26 Study: Key Findings</h4>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm">
        <li><strong>246,822</strong> U.S. adults with atherosclerotic heart disease studied (123,411 matched pairs)</li>
        <li><strong>46%</strong> reduction in major adverse cardiac events (MACE) within one year</li>
        <li><strong>66%</strong> reduction in all-cause mortality</li>
        <li><strong>32%</strong> lower risk of heart attack</li>
        <li><strong>25%</strong> lower risk of stroke and heart failure</li>
        <li><strong>Study period:</strong> 2018–2025, using the TriNetX database</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <section id="the-numbers" class="reveal">
      <h2>The Numbers That Got Cardiologists' Attention</h2>

      <p>The ACC.26 study, led by Robert Nguyen, MD, a resident physician at the University of California, Riverside, was a retrospective cohort analysis — not a randomized trial. It used the TriNetX database to examine 246,822 U.S. adults aged 50 and older with diagnosed atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease. Half had received a herpes zoster vaccine (either Shingrix or the older live-attenuated Zostavax). Half had not. The groups were matched on demographics and socioeconomic factors.</p>

      <p>The results were striking across every measured outcome. Within one year of vaccination, the vaccinated group experienced 46% fewer major adverse cardiac events. Their heart attack risk was 32% lower. Stroke risk fell by 25%. Heart failure risk dropped by 25%. And all-cause mortality — death from any cause — was 66% lower in the vaccinated group.</p>

      <p>"This vaccine has been found over and over again to have cardioprotective effects for reducing heart attack, stroke and death," Nguyen said. The reductions, he added, are "comparable to the benefits seen from quitting smoking."</p>

      <p>That comparison is worth sitting with. Smoking cessation is arguably the single most impactful lifestyle change a person with cardiovascular disease can make. A vaccine that delivers a comparable magnitude of risk reduction — with two injections and no behavioral modification — would be a profound addition to the preventive cardiology toolkit. If the data hold up.</p>

      <p>This was not an isolated finding. In May 2025, a study published in the <em>European Heart Journal</em> by Professor Dong Keon Yon and colleagues at Kyung Hee University in Seoul analyzed 1,271,922 adults aged 50 and older in South Korea. Vaccinated individuals had a 23% lower risk of cardiovascular events overall, a 26% lower risk of major adverse cardiac events, and a 22% lower risk of coronary heart disease. The protective effect was strongest in the two to three years after vaccination but remained detectable for up to eight years.</p>

      <p>Then in August 2025, the European Society of Cardiology presented the first global meta-analysis on the subject — a systematic review of eight observational studies and one randomized controlled trial. It found an 18% reduction in cardiovascular events among vaccinated adults across multiple populations and geographies.</p>

      <p>Three studies. Three continents. Three different methodologies. The same direction.</p>
    </section>

    <aside class="pull-quote reveal">
      <p>"These reductions are comparable to the benefits seen from quitting smoking."</p>
    </aside>

    <section id="the-virus-inside-your-arteries" class="reveal">
      <h2>The Virus Inside Your Arteries</h2>

      <p>The mechanism is not fully understood, but the leading hypothesis is both plausible and well-supported. It starts with what herpes zoster actually does when it reactivates.</p>

      <p>Varicella-zoster virus (VZV) is a herpesvirus. After the initial chickenpox infection — which most people over 40 experienced in childhood — the virus goes dormant in the dorsal root ganglia, clusters of nerve cells along the spine. It can stay there for decades. When immune surveillance weakens, typically with aging or immunosuppression, the virus reactivates. It travels along sensory nerve fibers to the skin, producing the characteristic painful, blistering rash of shingles.</p>

      <p>But the virus does not limit itself to the skin. It can spread along nerve fibers to blood vessels, particularly cerebral and coronary arteries. When it infects the vascular endothelium — the single-cell-thick lining of blood vessels — it triggers a cascade of inflammatory responses. The arterial wall becomes inflamed. The endothelium becomes dysfunctional. The blood's tendency to clot increases.</p>

      <h3>The Vascular Damage Pathway</h3>

      <p>A 2022 review in <em>Monaldi Archives for Chest Disease</em> detailed several mechanisms by which VZV causes cardiovascular harm:</p>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Vasculopathy.</strong> The virus can infect arterial smooth muscle cells, causing a noncytolytic infection that remodels the vessel wall. The result is narrowing, weakening, and increased vulnerability to rupture — the pathological basis of stroke and aneurysm.</li>
        <li><strong>Prothrombotic state.</strong> Herpes zoster triggers intense immune activation that increases clotting factors in the bloodstream. This raises the risk of thrombosis — the formation of blood clots that can block arteries feeding the heart or brain.</li>
        <li><strong>Systemic inflammation.</strong> Even after the rash resolves, the inflammatory signature of VZV reactivation can persist. Elevated levels of pro-inflammatory cytokines — IL-6, TNF-alpha, C-reactive protein — are markers of ongoing vascular stress that accelerate atherosclerosis.</li>
      </ul>

      <p>The epidemiological data match the mechanistic story. A 2017 meta-analysis in <em>BMC Infectious Diseases</em> found that stroke risk increased by 78% in the first month after a shingles episode, 43% at three months, and remained elevated by 20% at one year. Herpes zoster ophthalmicus — shingles affecting the eye region, which tracks to cerebral arteries — carried a stroke risk more than double the baseline in the first month.</p>

      <p>The cardiovascular harm from shingles is not theoretical. It is documented, dose-dependent, and time-dependent. Preventing the infection prevents the damage.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="not-just-shingles" class="reveal">
      <h2>Not Just Shingles: The Vaccine-Heart Connection</h2>

      <p>Here is where the story gets more interesting — and more complicated. The shingles vaccine is not the only vaccine that appears to protect the heart.</p>

      <p>The influenza vaccine has been shown across multiple randomized controlled trials to reduce cardiovascular events. A meta-analysis of studies involving over 9,000 patients found a 26% decrease in heart attacks and a 33% reduction in cardiovascular deaths among flu vaccine recipients. A 2021 randomized trial found that people vaccinated shortly after hospitalization for a heart attack had a 28% lower risk of dying, having another heart attack, or needing urgent revascularization over the following year.</p>

      <p>COVID-19 vaccination has shown similar cardiovascular associations in observational data. The BCG tuberculosis vaccine has long been known to confer "heterologous" protection — benefits that extend far beyond tuberculosis — likely through a process called trained immunity, where innate immune cells undergo epigenetic reprogramming that makes them respond more effectively to unrelated threats.</p>

      <p>This pattern raises a question that is central to interpreting the shingles vaccine data: is the cardiovascular protection specific to preventing VZV reactivation, or is it partly a non-specific immune benefit of vaccination itself?</p>

      <h3>Two Hypotheses, Not Mutually Exclusive</h3>

      <p>The first hypothesis is straightforward. VZV causes vascular damage. The vaccine prevents VZV reactivation. Therefore the vaccine prevents the vascular damage. This is the "infection prevention" model, and the mechanistic evidence supports it strongly.</p>

      <p>The second hypothesis is subtler. Shingrix contains AS01B, one of the most potent adjuvants in clinical use — a combination of monophosphoryl lipid A (MPL) and QS-21 formulated in liposomes. AS01B produces vigorous cell-mediated immunity. It also produces significant reactogenicity: sore arms, fatigue, fevers. That reactogenicity is a sign of intense innate immune activation. Whether that activation produces trained immunity effects — lasting changes in how the immune system handles inflammation and vascular repair — is not yet known, but not implausible.</p>

      <p>It may be both. A vaccine that prevents a vascular infection and simultaneously tunes the innate immune system would be, in some sense, a cardiovascular intervention from two directions. The evidence does not yet distinguish between these mechanisms. But the effect sizes — larger than what flu vaccination achieves, and present even in populations without documented shingles episodes — suggest the answer is not simple.</p>
    </section>

    <aside class="pull-quote reveal">
      <p>"A vaccine that prevents a vascular infection and simultaneously tunes the innate immune system would be a cardiovascular intervention from two directions."</p>
    </aside>

    <section id="the-dementia-dividend" class="reveal">
      <h2>The Dementia Dividend</h2>

      <p>The cardiovascular story would be remarkable on its own. But the shingles vaccine has a second act that is equally striking: it appears to reduce dementia risk.</p>

      <p>A study published in <em>Nature Medicine</em> in 2024 exploited a natural experiment in Wales, where eligibility for the shingles vaccine was determined by exact date of birth — people born before a specific cutoff were eligible; those born after were not. This quasi-random assignment allowed researchers to estimate causal effects with a rigor uncommon in vaccine studies. Among more than 200,000 adults aged 65 and older, vaccination was associated with a 17% increase in diagnosis-free time, translating into 164 additional days lived without a dementia diagnosis for those who were eventually affected.</p>

      <p>A follow-up study published in <em>Nature</em> in April 2025, from the same Stanford-led research group, confirmed and extended the finding: shingles vaccination was associated with a 20% lower risk of developing dementia over seven years. The effect was robust across multiple analytical approaches and sensitivity analyses.</p>

      <p>Then in December 2025, a study published in <em>Cell</em> found that the vaccine may benefit people who already have dementia — slowing the progression of the disease.</p>

      <p>And at IDWeek 2025, an analysis of over 174,000 U.S. adults found that shingles vaccine recipients had a 50% lower risk of vascular dementia specifically — along with a 27% lower risk of blood clots, a 25% lower risk of heart attack or stroke, and a 21% lower risk of death.</p>

      <p>The connection between cardiovascular protection and dementia protection is not coincidental. Vascular dementia is directly caused by impaired blood flow to the brain. If the shingles vaccine prevents vascular damage and thrombosis, it would be expected to reduce vascular dementia. And the mechanistic link to Alzheimer's may run through the same inflammatory pathways: VZV has been associated with amyloid deposition and tau protein aggregation — the hallmark pathologies of Alzheimer's disease.</p>

      <p>A single vaccine that meaningfully reduces heart attack, stroke, and dementia. That is not the kind of intervention that comes along very often.</p>
    </section>

    <div class="info-card my-12 reveal">
      <h4 class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold mb-3 text-primary-700 dark:text-primary-400">Beyond Shingles: Other Documented Benefits</h4>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm">
        <li><strong>20%</strong> lower dementia risk over 7 years (Nature, April 2025)</li>
        <li><strong>164 days</strong> additional diagnosis-free time for those who develop dementia</li>
        <li><strong>50%</strong> lower risk of vascular dementia (IDWeek 2025)</li>
        <li><strong>23%</strong> lower cardiovascular event risk lasting up to 8 years (European Heart Journal, 2025)</li>
        <li><strong>97.2%</strong> efficacy against shingles in adults 50+ (its original purpose)</li>
        <li><strong>1 in 3</strong> Americans will develop shingles in their lifetime without vaccination</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <section id="the-skeptics-case" class="reveal">
      <h2>The Skeptics' Case</h2>

      <p>The evidence is compelling. It is not bulletproof. Any intellectually honest assessment of this data must acknowledge what it cannot yet prove.</p>

      <h3>The Confounding Problem</h3>

      <p>Almost all of the cardiovascular and dementia evidence comes from observational studies, not randomized controlled trials designed to test cardiac outcomes. The ESC meta-analysis explicitly noted that eight of its nine included studies were observational. Observational studies, no matter how well-matched, cannot fully eliminate confounding.</p>

      <p>The most obvious confounder: people who get vaccinated tend to be healthier. They see doctors more regularly. They take their medications. They exercise more. They eat better. This is the "healthy vaccinee" effect, and it plagues every observational vaccine study. Researchers in the ACC.26 study controlled for demographics and socioeconomic factors. The Korean study adjusted for lifestyle variables. But residual confounding — unmeasured differences between the groups — can never be entirely ruled out in this design.</p>

      <h3>Effect Size Concerns</h3>

      <p>A 66% reduction in all-cause mortality is enormous. Suspiciously enormous, some would argue. No single intervention in cardiology — not statins, not blood pressure medication, not even coronary artery bypass surgery — produces a 66% mortality reduction in a broad population with atherosclerotic disease. When effect sizes are much larger than what well-established interventions produce, it is worth asking whether confounding is inflating the estimate.</p>

      <p>The more conservative numbers — the 18% reduction from the global meta-analysis, or the 23% from the Korean study — are more plausible as genuine treatment effects. But they are also less headline-worthy, which creates its own distortion in how the evidence is perceived.</p>

      <h3>The Randomized Trial Gap</h3>

      <p>The definitive test would be a large, multicenter randomized controlled trial with cardiovascular events as the primary endpoint. No such trial exists. The one randomized trial included in the ESC meta-analysis was a pooled safety analysis of Phase 3 Shingrix trials — it was not designed or powered to assess cardiac outcomes. Running a placebo-controlled cardiac trial of the shingles vaccine now would be ethically complicated, given that the vaccine is already recommended for adults over 50. You would be withholding a proven treatment from the control group.</p>

      <p>This is the paradox of off-target vaccine benefits. Once a vaccine is approved and recommended for its primary indication, generating randomized evidence for secondary benefits becomes nearly impossible. We are left with the observational data — which is abundant, consistent, and directionally clear, but not causally definitive.</p>

      <h3>Population Generalizability</h3>

      <p>The Korean study used an Asian cohort exclusively. The ACC.26 study was U.S.-based but derived from electronic health records, which have their own biases. The Welsh natural experiment focused on a specific demographic in the UK. Whether the cardiovascular benefits are equally strong across all populations, ethnicities, and risk profiles is genuinely unknown.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="who-should-care" class="reveal">
      <h2>Who Should Care — and Who Already Does</h2>

      <p>The CDC already recommends Shingrix for all adults aged 50 and older, and for younger adults with weakened immune systems. That recommendation is based on shingles prevention. The cardiovascular and neurological data are not yet part of the official rationale.</p>

      <p>But cardiologists have noticed. In 2025, the American College of Cardiology published an Expert Consensus Statement on adult immunizations as part of cardiovascular care — the first time the ACC formally integrated vaccination into its preventive cardiology guidance.</p>

      <p>One in three Americans will develop shingles in their lifetime without vaccination. The incidence rises sharply with age: approximately 10 cases per 1,000 people in the 50-59 age group, climbing to 24.5 per 1,000 in those over 70. About one million cases occur annually in the United States alone. Between 10% and 18% of those develop postherpetic neuralgia — chronic, debilitating nerve pain that can last months or years.</p>

      <p>Yet vaccination rates remain low. As of the most recent CDC data, only about 26% of adults aged 50 and older had ever received a shingles vaccine. The barriers are familiar: cost (Shingrix runs roughly $200 per dose without insurance, with two doses required), reactogenicity (the side effects — fatigue, muscle pain, headache, fever — are more intense than a typical flu shot), and simple lack of urgency about a disease most people think of as merely unpleasant rather than dangerous.</p>

      <p>The cardiovascular data may change that calculus. If the shingles vaccine is not just preventing a rash but meaningfully reducing heart attack, stroke, and dementia risk, the benefit-to-cost ratio shifts dramatically. A two-dose vaccine series that provides years of cardiovascular protection — in addition to its primary purpose — starts to look less like an optional preventive measure and more like a critical component of healthy aging.</p>
    </section>

    <section id="what-we-know-and-dont" class="reveal">
      <h2>What We Actually Know and Don't</h2>

      <p>Here is where the evidence stands, without inflation or deflation.</p>

      <p><strong>Well-established:</strong> Herpes zoster (shingles) causes vascular damage. The virus infects arterial walls, triggers inflammation, and promotes blood clot formation. Shingles episodes are followed by measurably increased rates of stroke and heart attack, with the highest risk in the first month and declining over the subsequent year. The shingles vaccine is highly effective at preventing shingles.</p>

      <p><strong>Strong but not definitive:</strong> Multiple large observational studies, across diverse populations and methodologies, show that shingles vaccination is associated with lower rates of cardiovascular events, cardiovascular death, all-cause mortality, and dementia. The effect sizes range from 18% to 46% for cardiac events depending on the study and population. One quasi-randomized natural experiment found a 20% reduction in dementia risk. These findings are consistent and biologically plausible.</p>

      <p><strong>Uncertain:</strong> Whether the cardiovascular protection is entirely due to preventing VZV reactivation or partly due to broader immune modulation. Whether the very large effect sizes reported in some studies are inflated by residual confounding. Whether the benefits are equal across all populations. How long the cardiovascular protection lasts beyond eight years.</p>

      <p><strong>Unknown:</strong> The results of a properly powered randomized trial with cardiovascular endpoints — because none exists, and none is likely to be conducted.</p>

      <p>What we are looking at is a body of evidence that is large, directionally consistent, mechanistically supported, and clinically significant — but not yet causally proven by the gold standard of a randomized trial. In the hierarchy of medical evidence, that puts it in the same category as many public health recommendations that we act on routinely: strong enough to take seriously, not strong enough to call settled science.</p>

      <p>Dr. Anthony Komaroff, editor-in-chief of the <em>Harvard Health Letter</em>, described the cardiac protection as "icing on the cake" — an unexpected additional benefit atop a vaccine already justified by its primary indication. He received Shingrix promptly upon its availability. He has remained shingles-free since.</p>

      <p>The difference between a vaccine that prevents a rash and a vaccine that may prevent heart attacks, strokes, and dementia is not pharmacological. The molecule is the same. The difference is in what we have learned about the virus it targets — and in the dawning recognition that chronic infections, even ones we have trivialized for decades, exact a vascular toll that compounds silently until it kills.</p>

      <p>The shingles shot was never designed to protect the heart. The heart does not appear to care about the designer's intentions.</p>
    </section>

